<?php

namespace Database\Seeders;

use App\Models\ContentBlock;
use Illuminate\Database\Seeder;

class ContentBlockSeeder extends Seeder
{
    /**
     * Seed the service pages' article content as editable blocks.
     *
     * Non-destructive: a page is only populated when it currently has NO
     * blocks. Pages the admin has already added to or edited are left
     * untouched, so running this seeder never wipes admin changes. This
     * makes it safe to run on every deploy to fill in any empty pages.
     *
     * To intentionally reset a page back to these defaults, delete its
     * blocks in the admin panel (or the DB) first, then re-run the seeder.
     */
    public function run(): void
    {
        $pages = [
            'heating' => $this->heating(),
            'cooling' => $this->cooling(),
            'plumbing' => $this->plumbing(),
            'electrical' => $this->electrical(),
            'indoor-air-quality' => $this->airQuality(),
            'drains' => $this->drains(),
            'commercial' => $this->commercial(),
        ];

        foreach ($pages as $page => $blocks) {
            // Skip any page that already has content — preserves admin edits.
            if (ContentBlock::where('page', $page)->exists()) {
                continue;
            }

            foreach ($blocks as $i => $block) {
                ContentBlock::create(array_merge($block, ['page' => $page, 'position' => $i]));
            }
        }
    }

    private function heating(): array
    {
        return [
            ['type' => 'section', 'heading' => 'Furnace Service Overview', 'body' => "A furnace is the key component of your home's heating system, responsible for generating and distributing warmth throughout your living space. Keeping it running well ensures your home stays safe and comfortable through the coldest months of the New Jersey winter.\n\nWhether you need a quick repair, a seasonal tune-up, or a full system replacement, our licensed technicians handle every type of heating equipment with upfront pricing and same-day response."],
            ['type' => 'section', 'heading' => 'Why Maintenance Is Important', 'body' => "Regular maintenance is crucial for your furnace to operate efficiently and reliably. A short annual check-up protects your investment and your comfort.\n\nPrevent Unexpected Breakdowns — Regular inspections catch small problems early, before they turn into a no-heat emergency on the coldest night of the year.\n\nImprove Energy Efficiency — A well-maintained furnace runs more efficiently, lowering your energy consumption and your monthly utility bills.\n\nExtend Equipment Lifespan — Consistent tune-ups keep your system running longer, delaying the cost of a full replacement for years."],
            ['type' => 'image', 'heading' => 'Guardian Air technician servicing a furnace in a New Jersey home', 'image_path' => '/img/heating-hero.webp'],
            ['type' => 'section', 'heading' => 'When To Replace', 'body' => "Deciding when to replace your furnace can be challenging. Consider these signs.\n\nAge — If your system is more than 15 years old, it may be time to consider replacement. Older units are far less efficient and more prone to failure.\n\nFrequent Repairs — If you're calling for repairs every season, it's often more cost-effective to replace the unit than to keep paying to fix it.\n\nUneven Heating — Cold spots and rooms that never warm up properly are a sign your furnace is struggling to keep up.\n\nRising Energy Bills — An unexplained jump in your heating costs usually means your furnace is losing efficiency as it wears out."],
            ['type' => 'section', 'heading' => 'Types Of Furnaces', 'body' => "Here's a quick guide to the types of heating systems we install and service.\n\nGas Furnaces — The most common and cost-effective option, burning natural gas for fast, powerful heat throughout your home.\n\nElectric Furnaces — A lower upfront cost and a great fit for homes without a gas line, using electric heating elements.\n\nOil Furnaces — Common in older New Jersey homes, burning heating oil to deliver strong, reliable heat output.\n\nHeat Pumps — Energy-efficient electric systems that both heat and cool, ideal for milder climates and year-round comfort.\n\nBoilers — Provide steady radiant warmth through hot water, feeding radiators or in-floor heating systems."],
            ['type' => 'faq', 'heading' => 'How often should I service my furnace?', 'body' => 'At least once a year — ideally in early fall, before heating season starts. An annual tune-up keeps your system efficient, catches small issues early, and helps avoid mid-winter breakdowns.'],
            ['type' => 'faq', 'heading' => 'What are the common signs that my furnace needs repairs?', 'body' => 'Watch for unusual noises (banging, rattling, or screeching), weak or uneven heat, a sudden jump in energy bills, frequent on-off cycling, or a yellow burner flame instead of blue.'],
            ['type' => 'faq', 'heading' => 'Can I fix my furnace myself?', 'body' => 'Basic upkeep like changing the air filter is fine to do yourself. Anything involving gas lines, electrical components, or internal parts should be handled by a licensed technician for your safety.'],
            ['type' => 'faq', 'heading' => 'Why is my furnace blowing cold air?', 'body' => 'The most common causes are a thermostat set to "ON" instead of "AUTO," a clogged air filter, a pilot or ignition problem, or restricted gas flow. We can pinpoint the exact issue quickly.'],
            ['type' => 'faq', 'heading' => 'Why is my HVAC not heating?', 'body' => 'It could be a tripped breaker, incorrect thermostat settings, a dirty filter restricting airflow, an ignition failure, or a faulty blower motor. A diagnostic visit will identify the cause.'],
            ['type' => 'faq', 'heading' => "Why isn't my furnace turning on?", 'body' => "Check that the power switch is on, the thermostat has fresh batteries, and the breaker hasn't tripped. If those are fine, it's likely an ignition, control board, or safety-switch issue."],
            ['type' => 'faq', 'heading' => 'What should I do if my heat stops working?', 'body' => 'Confirm the thermostat is set to heat, check the breaker and furnace switch, and replace a dirty filter. If heat still doesn\'t return, call us for same-day emergency service.'],
            ['type' => 'faq', 'heading' => 'What should I do if my boiler stops working?', 'body' => 'Check the pressure gauge, pilot light, and power supply — low pressure or a tripped reset button are common culprits. If the problem persists, a technician should inspect it.'],
            ['type' => 'faq', 'heading' => 'What should I do if my HVAC freezes in winter?', 'body' => 'Turn the system off to let it thaw, then check for blocked airflow and a dirty filter. If ice keeps forming, shut it down and call a pro to prevent damage to the unit.'],
            ['type' => 'faq', 'heading' => 'Can a leaking boiler be repaired?', 'body' => 'Often yes — leaks from valves, seals, or fittings are usually repairable. A leaking heat exchanger, however, typically means the boiler needs to be replaced.'],
            ['type' => 'faq', 'heading' => 'Can a furnace leak water from the bottom?', 'body' => 'Yes. On high-efficiency furnaces this usually points to a clogged condensate line or drain. It should be addressed promptly to avoid water damage and corrosion.'],
            ['type' => 'faq', 'heading' => 'What does HVAC maintenance include?', 'body' => 'A full tune-up covers inspecting and cleaning key components, replacing filters, checking gas or refrigerant levels, testing safety controls, and verifying the system runs efficiently.'],
            ['type' => 'faq', 'heading' => 'What does an HVAC inspection include?', 'body' => 'We examine the heating and cooling components, electrical connections, airflow, thermostat operation, and all safety systems, then give you a clear report on the system\'s condition.'],
            ['type' => 'faq', 'heading' => 'What does an HVAC technician do?', 'body' => 'A licensed HVAC technician installs, repairs, and maintains heating, cooling, and ventilation systems — diagnosing problems and keeping your equipment running safely and efficiently.'],
        ];
    }

