            ['type' => 'section', 'heading' => 'Electrical Services We Offer', 'body' => "Here's a quick guide to the electrical work we install, repair, and maintain.\n\nPanel Upgrades — Modernize your electrical panel to safely handle today's appliances, EV chargers, and high-demand circuits with confidence.\n\nWiring & Rewiring — New circuits, full-home rewires, and repairs to damaged or outdated wiring, all done to current code for lasting safety.\n\nLighting & Fixtures — Recessed lighting, ceiling fans, outdoor and accent fixtures installed cleanly to brighten and elevate every room.\n\nOutlets & Switches — New outlets, GFCI installations, dimmers, and smart switches added wherever you need safe, convenient power.\n\nGenerators & EV Chargers — Standby generator hookups and Level 2 EV charger installs that keep you powered and ready for the future."],
            ['type' => 'faq', 'heading' => 'How do I know if my electrical panel needs an upgrade?', 'body' => 'If you have a fuse box, a panel rated under 100 amps, frequently tripping breakers, or you\'re adding major appliances or an EV charger, it\'s likely time for an upgrade. We can assess your panel and recommend the right capacity for your home.'],
            ['type' => 'faq', 'heading' => 'Why do my circuit breakers keep tripping?', 'body' => 'Repeated tripping usually means a circuit is overloaded, or there\'s a short circuit or ground fault. It\'s the breaker doing its job, but persistent tripping points to an underlying issue a licensed electrician should diagnose.'],
            ['type' => 'faq', 'heading' => 'Is it safe to do my own electrical work?', 'body' => 'Swapping a light bulb or resetting a tripped breaker is fine. Anything involving wiring, outlets, panels, or new circuits should be left to a licensed electrician — DIY electrical mistakes can cause fires, shocks, and failed inspections.'],
            ['type' => 'faq', 'heading' => 'What causes flickering or dimming lights?', 'body' => 'Flickering often comes from loose wiring, an overloaded circuit, a failing fixture, or a panel that can\'t keep up with demand. If it happens throughout the house, it\'s worth having the system inspected.'],
            ['type' => 'faq', 'heading' => 'Why do my outlets feel warm or spark?', 'body' => 'A warm outlet, sparking, or a burning smell signals loose connections, overloading, or damaged wiring, all serious fire risks. Stop using the outlet, turn off the circuit, and call us for same-day service.'],
            ['type' => 'faq', 'heading' => 'What is a GFCI outlet and where do I need them?', 'body' => 'A GFCI (Ground Fault Circuit Interrupter) outlet shuts off power instantly if it detects a fault, preventing shocks. Code requires them in kitchens, bathrooms, garages, basements, and outdoor areas.'],
            ['type' => 'faq', 'heading' => 'Can you install an EV charger at my home?', 'body' => 'Yes. We install Level 2 EV chargers, including any panel upgrades or dedicated circuits needed to support them safely. We\'ll evaluate your panel capacity and recommend the best setup for your vehicle.'],
            ['type' => 'faq', 'heading' => 'Do I need a permit for electrical work?', 'body' => 'Most electrical work — panel upgrades, new circuits, and rewiring — requires a permit and inspection. As licensed electricians, we handle the permitting process and ensure every job passes inspection.'],
            ['type' => 'faq', 'heading' => "How often should I have my home's wiring inspected?", 'body' => "We recommend an inspection every few years for newer homes, and sooner for homes over 25 years old or any home you've just purchased. Aluminum wiring and older panels should be checked promptly."],
            ['type' => 'faq', 'heading' => 'What should I do during an electrical emergency?', 'body' => 'If you smell burning, see sparks, or have exposed wiring, shut off power at the breaker if it\'s safe to do so and keep away from the area. Then call us — we offer same-day emergency electrical service.'],
        ];
    }

    private function airQuality(): array
    {
        return [
            ['type' => 'section', 'heading' => 'Indoor Air Quality Overview', 'body' => "The air inside your home can be up to five times more polluted than the air outside. Dust, pollen, pet dander, mold spores, and volatile organic compounds all circulate through your HVAC system — and into your lungs. We help you take control.\n\nOur team assesses your home's air quality and recommends the right mix of filtration, humidity control, and purification. From whole-home air purifiers to duct cleaning and UV germicidal lights, we have solutions for every budget and concern."],
            ['type' => 'section', 'heading' => 'Why Indoor Air Quality Matters', 'body' => "The air you breathe at home directly affects your health and comfort. Investing in better indoor air quality pays off every single day.\n\nProtect Your Health — Indoor air can be up to five times more polluted than outdoor air. Cleaner air reduces allergens, irritants, and airborne contaminants that aggravate asthma and allergies.\n\nBreathe Easier Every Day — Balanced humidity and proper filtration help everyone in your home sleep better, breathe easier, and feel more comfortable year-round.\n\nProtect Your Home & HVAC — Controlling dust, moisture, and contaminants keeps your HVAC system running efficiently and helps prevent mold growth and damage to your home."],
            ['type' => 'image', 'heading' => 'Guardian Air technician installing an air purification system in a New Jersey home', 'image_path' => '/img/air-quality-hero.webp'],
            ['type' => 'section', 'heading' => 'Signs Of Poor Air Quality', 'body' => "Poor indoor air quality isn't always obvious. Watch for these common warning signs.\n\nPersistent Dust — If dust resettles on surfaces almost as soon as you clean, your air is likely full of fine particles your filtration system is missing.\n\nAllergy & Respiratory Symptoms — Frequent sneezing, congestion, headaches, or irritated eyes indoors often point to high levels of pollen, dander, or other airborne irritants.\n\nMusty or Stale Odors — Lingering smells that won't go away can signal mold, excess moisture, or stagnant air that needs better ventilation and purification.\n\nHumidity Problems — Condensation on windows, clammy air, or overly dry air that causes static and cracked skin all indicate your home needs humidity control.\n\nNoticing any of these in your home? Schedule an air quality assessment and we'll recommend the right solution."],
            ['type' => 'section', 'heading' => 'Air Quality Solutions We Offer', 'body' => "Here's a quick guide to the indoor air quality solutions we install and service.\n\nAir Purifiers — Whole-home systems that capture allergens, dust, smoke, and microscopic particles before they circulate through your living space.\n\nHumidifiers — Add balanced moisture to dry winter air, easing dry skin, static, and respiratory discomfort while protecting woodwork and furniture.\n\nDehumidifiers — Remove excess moisture to prevent mold, mildew, and that heavy, clammy feeling during humid New Jersey summers.\n\nUV Germicidal Lights — Installed in your HVAC system to neutralize mold, bacteria, and viruses as air passes through the coil and ductwork.\n\nDuct Cleaning — Clears built-up dust, debris, and allergens from your ductwork so the air delivered to every room is as clean as possible."],
            ['type' => 'faq', 'heading' => 'How do I know if my home has poor indoor air quality?', 'body' => 'Common warning signs include persistent dust, lingering musty odors, increased allergy or respiratory symptoms indoors, and humidity problems like condensation or overly dry air. An air quality test gives you a clear picture.'],
            ['type' => 'faq', 'heading' => 'What causes poor indoor air quality?', 'body' => 'Dust, pollen, pet dander, mold spores, volatile organic compounds (VOCs), and excess or insufficient humidity all reduce air quality. Many of these contaminants circulate through your HVAC system and into the air you breathe.'],
            ['type' => 'faq', 'heading' => 'How often should I change my air filter?', 'body' => 'Most standard filters should be replaced every one to three months, depending on the filter type, whether you have pets, and how often the system runs. High-efficiency and allergy-rated filters may have different intervals.'],
            ['type' => 'faq', 'heading' => 'Do air purifiers really work?', 'body' => 'Yes. A properly sized whole-home air purifier captures airborne particles like dust, pollen, smoke, and dander before they recirculate, noticeably reducing allergens and improving the air throughout your home.'],
            ['type' => 'faq', 'heading' => 'What is the ideal indoor humidity level?', 'body' => 'Most homes are most comfortable between 30% and 50% relative humidity. Too low causes dry skin and static; too high encourages mold and dust mites. Humidifiers and dehumidifiers help you hit the right balance.'],
            ['type' => 'faq', 'heading' => 'How does a UV germicidal light improve air quality?', 'body' => 'UV lights installed in your HVAC system neutralize mold, bacteria, and viruses as air passes over the coil and through the ductwork, helping keep your system clean and the circulating air healthier.'],
            ['type' => 'faq', 'heading' => 'Is duct cleaning worth it?', 'body' => 'Duct cleaning is worthwhile when there\'s visible mold, excessive dust, debris, or signs of pests in the ductwork. Clean ducts help your system run efficiently and stop recirculating contaminants through your home.'],
            ['type' => 'faq', 'heading' => 'Can poor air quality affect my allergies or asthma?', 'body' => 'Absolutely. Airborne allergens such as dust, pollen, pet dander, and mold spores are common asthma and allergy triggers. Improving filtration and controlling humidity often reduces symptoms significantly.'],
            ['type' => 'faq', 'heading' => 'What is the difference between an air purifier and an air filter?', 'body' => 'A filter traps particles as air passes through it, while a purifier actively treats the air using advanced filtration and technologies like UV light or ionization to remove or neutralize a wider range of contaminants.'],
